snippet.textDisplay:
Hey Mark; I’d love to make a change for the better in my family, but we usually can only afford cheaper meats already, so there’s really no way these type of expensive burger substitutes could make it into our diet and still fit within our budget.

I’m not saying I don’t have an obligation to the planet to do it anyway - or to just eat PB&J instead of meat, but for the majority of Americans who would be willing to make a switch to a full plant based diet via the meat substitutes and not just giving up meat entirely, I imagine it would be out of reach due to budgeting reasons, as it is for me and my family.

snippet.textDisplay: With all due respect, you're very intelligent as an engineer, but you know nothing about nutrition. Your points for why a plant based diet is so glorious (in terms of nutrition) have also all been debunked. You pulled them straight from a Netflix documentary that was entirely subjective and then committed an appeal to authority... 🤦‍♂️ Should've had an unbiased nutrition expert on like Bio Layne... That's literally one of the engineering codes, don't claim to be an expert in an area you're not an expert. And then you go on to talk about the exchange of beef for grains... Ah yes a full grain diet is so nutritional! The actual benefits from veganism are minimal, especially when 30% of our meat industry actually goes back into animal food in the form of cat and dog food. The large portion of emissions from the meat industry that come from mass production would also become associated with plant based foods once they become mass produces. As meat consumption continues to rise in the US (and globally), our emissions continue to fall, and the level of plant based eaters has only slightly risen by a fairly statistically irrelevant amount (depending on which surveys/studies you use). That being said, many of the climate change switches are like this. They seem great on the outside but aren't much better on the inside especially when cost and freedom are added in. For example the paper industry is responsible for massively more pollution than polymers and yet we made a switch to "paper is better" 🤷‍♂️ just seems like this video is more of an agenda driven video than a science and engineering one. I come to this channel to learn and get interested in new things in my career path, but after knowing that many of the claims in this video are illogical, false or misleading, it makes me second guess the rest of your work. You say costs will go down from innovative solutions but that's true of all industries and that's the real reason emissions would drop. As for it being half the cost... I've yet to see even the worst veggie burger run for less than 80/20 Chuck (and I work part time in a butcher shop)...

snippet.textDisplay: I was a lot like you this time last year, Mark (minus the YouTube stardom and casual lunches with Bill Gates, of course). I ate meat with basically every single meal, and considered no plate complete without it. At the same time I had been growing increasingly aware of my environmental impact, and watched some Kurzgesagt videos about the meat industry and meat consumption. I was kind of shocked and made the change, initially, to go meatless during the week, figuring that if someone like me couldn't make a change like that, any talk on reverting environmental damage was probably a non-starter. I'm not going to preach to anyone about going meatless full-time because I do still believe there are benefits to having a balanced diet, but I wanted to say thanks for making this video anyway. Sparking some interest in people to go meatless, even if only once a week, could have quite the ripple.
